00:03:06.919 --> 00:03:11.399
I'm thinking, Oh, well, that project got canceled or that project failed, or, or that whole

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:16.800
initiative got canned. Is there a way you can think of to like some advice you could

00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:22.240
give for people on how to phrase or structure things or approach things in that situation?

00:03:22.919 --> 00:03:31.119
Yeah, I think a lot of times when we think about impact, we think, therefore, the company

00:03:31.119 --> 00:03:36.759
made this decision, they launched this feature, they made this amount of money. And there's

00:03:36.759 --> 00:03:42.440
a broader definition of impact, actually, when we try something out from a data science

00:03:42.440 --> 00:03:46.559
perspective, and it doesn't work, well, we actually just learned something new, we learn

00:03:46.559 --> 00:03:52.279
this data isn't predictive of this outcome, we learn this technique falls short. And

00:03:52.279 --> 00:03:57.759
sometimes the absence of something working saves the business time, it means we don't

00:03:57.759 --> 00:04:01.759
need to invest further there, it means we can ask other questions, we can focus on other

00:04:01.759 --> 00:04:08.320
hypotheses. And that in and of itself is valuable, you are moving the research of your

00:04:08.559 --> 00:04:13.839
company forward when you find out something doesn't work, because it means, well, someone

00:04:13.839 --> 00:04:18.559
else doesn't need to do that. You've saved time, you're moving forward. And so I think,

00:04:18.839 --> 00:04:22.559
you know, when we think about these, these research studies, or these analysis techniques,

00:04:22.600 --> 00:04:27.720
it's not just about what answer did you get? But what are your business stakeholders care

00:04:27.720 --> 00:04:32.480
