00:05:42.559 --> 00:05:47.559
framework have you found most success using and I really like this because I've worked

00:05:47.559 --> 00:05:51.239
in all kinds of project management environments. And some of them I really don't like. So I'd

00:05:51.239 --> 00:05:52.359
love to know your opinion.

00:05:54.359 --> 00:05:55.320
Oh, that's a hard one.

00:05:55.679 --> 00:05:56.519
It is.

00:05:57.760 --> 00:06:02.920
So the truth is, you know, these projects are broken into phases, we need to understand

00:06:02.920 --> 00:06:08.079
the question, we need to decide on our technique. And then we actually need to do the

00:06:08.079 --> 00:06:15.119
analysis and iterate, etc. And, you know, I've worked on product development teams that

00:06:15.119 --> 00:06:20.959
use agile, I've worked on teams that use Kanban. And none of these are actually a great

00:06:20.959 --> 00:06:28.559
fit for data projects, because there is so much ambiguity. And so it's really, it's not

00:06:28.559 --> 00:06:33.959
that there is a best path here, it's about understanding how to chunk up your work and

00:06:33.959 --> 00:06:38.200
set expectations. Because if you know how to set expectations with your stakeholders,

00:06:38.440 --> 00:06:43.320
the actual project management framework itself is less important, but the framework is

00:06:43.320 --> 00:06:49.920
there to drive decisions, drive timelines, drive prioritization. And for data projects,

00:06:49.920 --> 00:06:54.760
it's often better to have a conversation, and then square peg round hole it into whatever

00:06:54.760 --> 00:06:59.799
company or whatever process your company is using. But I've never seen a process that like

00:06:59.839 --> 00:07:04.119
fits perfectly and seamlessly where you don't need to have that stakeholder conversation.

00:07:05.839 --> 00:07:10.959
Yeah, nothing is perfect. I feel like it's tough because teams are made up of individuals

00:07:10.959 --> 00:07:16.160
and individuals are all completely different people. And often, when I'm saying like, I've

00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:22.359
worked in project management styles that were really, really terrible. They were terrible

00:07:22.359 --> 00:07:26.920
for me, but they were not terrible for some other people on my teams. And that's always

00:07:26.920 --> 00:07:31.239
tricky, right? It's like, it's almost like teaching, everyone's going to be a different

00:07:31.239 --> 00:07:38.079
type of learner. One thing I also am curious about is something that I struggle with

00:07:38.079 --> 00:07:44.480
personally, advocating for taking the time to like sharpen your own axe. And we've talked

00:07:44.480 --> 00:07:49.359
about this on the Hangout before. But my question is, instead of like, hey, how do I convince

00:07:49.359 --> 00:07:54.880
my manager that I need time to sharpen my axe? How do I convince myself that it is okay

00:07:55.079 --> 00:08:02.359
to say, I need several hours a week to skill build when that doesn't have a product at

00:08:02.359 --> 00:08:04.119
the end of it to hand over to somebody?

00:08:04.119 --> 00:08:24.119
It's a little bit, it's a little bit goes back to our conversation about failure. And it's only failure if you don't take into account the learning opportunity and the fact that you're moving the conversation forward. If you are hyper laser focused on, I have to figure out the root

00:08:25.040 --> 00:08:44.280
cause of what drove this metric, or I have to just project out, forecast, whatever thing I'm forecasting. You're not thinking more holistically. And, you know, as AI becomes more and more popular, AI is able to, you know, point to these different techniques and

00:08:48.280 --> 00:08:48.760
methods.

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:50.719
That's the one.

00:08:50.719 --> 00:08:51.320
There it is.

00:08:52.400 --> 00:09:11.599
And what actually AI can't do, though, is add that, you know, human je ne sais quoi. And, you know, if we think about how can you be the best creative thinking human that is going to connect insights better than the people in the AI, you know, models around you,

00:09:12.080 --> 00:09:31.119
investing in your skill set is going to make you better. And sometimes it's not just about getting explicit permission from your manager, because if you want to spend two hours a week, your manager is not going to know what you're doing for two hours a week, you're going to be able to slide that in just fine. But it's about recognizing your impact doesn't come from just, you know,

00:09:32.080 --> 00:09:57.280
spending more time in Python and R, typing at the keyboard, trying to fit this model, your impact comes from your ability to think holistically. And you're not going to be able to think holistically without taking a step back and figuring out what do I need to invest in for myself, so that I, you know, like, it's invest in yourself for the sake of helping drive investment in your company. And you have to put your career first because no one else is going to do it for you.

00:09:57.840 --> 00:10:17.119
Oof. That is true. And that is so, so hard to swallow. Sometimes I really struggle with this. If anybody else does, I'm with you. We have another anonymous question in the chat that I really like. So I will highlight that for everybody in Slido. So you can see it and I'll put it in the chat here as well.

00:10:17.119 --> 00:10:31.359
And it is, given all the different teams and all the different people that you've worked with, what repeated forms of communication failures have you seen? And how can you now overcome them preemptively?

00:10:31.359 --> 00:11:00.000
Well, there's a lot of usage of words like failure in these questions. And I really try to move away from that mindset. You know, things are not so binary in terms of success and failure. But I'd say the constant throughout my career, regardless of whether I'm at a startup, if I'm working on slot machines, hair extensions, you know, helping out Facebook in India, the common thing is, I'm not going to be able to do that.

00:11:00.239 --> 00:11:22.000
The common thing is, people who are drawn to data careers, think differently, oftentimes, than the business people around them. And that means they also communicate differently. They focus on different things. I've been called pedantic many times in my career. Sometimes I take that as a compliment. And sometimes, whatever, I brush it off.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:50.000
But it's, I fixate on the details, and I'm paid to fixate on the details in ways that no one else around me is. And so the biggest theme in my career is, we're talking past each other. The business stakeholders don't fully understand my skill set, my tool set, and what I can actually accomplish. And until I really took a step back and spent more time talking to my stakeholders, I didn't really understand what they were trying to accomplish.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:12:11.000
And so it's really about having that conversation. You know, we all would love to just focus on coding, and not have to worry about the human element. But the truth is, those human connections and those human relationships, understanding what matters to the people around you, that's actually what's going to help you drive your impact forward. That's how you're going to build trust.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:37.000
That's how, you know, when your model doesn't produce the results you were hoping for, when you have that relationship, and you have that trust, and you have that understanding with your stakeholders, that's going to give you grace. And they're like, oh, you worked really hard, and now we know this methodology doesn't work out, and you can try this other thing. But that doesn't work unless you talk to each other. And there's this art to understanding, what are the questions my business stakeholders meant to ask?

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:49.000
Because sometimes they don't even know how to word their questions. Because as I said, they don't understand our skill sets and our tool set most of the time. And so how do you learn how to translate what they meant to ask you for?

00:12:50.000 --> 00:13:09.000
Yeah, that's a good one. My degrees, while they are statistical and mathy and stuff, come from a college of business. And so I got a bunch of business courses. And that was one of the biggest business analytics lessons for me in school. It was like over and over again. People are not going to know what they want.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:29.000
But it's the same education that my husband, who has an arts degree and worked in marketing and branding and logo creation, it was the same thing. He was taught, no one's going to know what they want. And half the job is you helping them figure out what they actually want, and then translating that into the stuff that you can give them.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:49.000
Fantastic advice. Thank you, anonymous asker, for your wonderful question. We have some non-anonymous questions popping up here. But I want to follow up with an anonymous one again, because it's right in line with what you just said. You said, I just want to stick to coding, and maybe that's not the best thing.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:14:06.000
This question is, as an R expert, R coding, programming language, I'm often encouraged to learn more about business context. Should coders go deep into domain knowledge or rather focus on building strong bridges with business experts? I feel I'd rather stick to what I do best and just code in R.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:32.000
So, I mean, that's a hard one. This is a really personal choice. Thinking about what you should be doing is a bit of a trap. Because, you know, I guess in the first three to five years of your career, you have to check a bunch of boxes, and it's about learning how to be effective and do effective analysis, find statistically significant results. And so you should be focusing on your hard skills those first three to five years.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:53.000
From there, when you play to your strengths, you're naturally going to be more inspired, more curious, and you're going to work harder than the people around you. And so if you focus on what you should pick up, well, all of the other people who are naturally inclined to that are going to do it better than you.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:15:11.000
And so if you force yourself, well, everyone says I should be doing this in Python, and then you force yourself, well, the problem is there's going to the next generation is going to be doing that much faster than you, and they're going to work harder than you and get further ahead than you. And so it's not about what you should or shouldn't be doing.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:28.000
But it's about where do you see yourself in five to 10 years? When the next technological sea change occurs, what are you doing now to make your skill set and your career trajectory robust against the next technological change?

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:43.000
You know, when I first started writing data pipelines, it was all in Bash, and I was managing a Hadoop server, and it was miserable. And I should have become an expert in Hadoop and Bash, and that skill set would serve me not at all today.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:16:08.000
It does help me have empathy for my data engineering partners. But if I had just invested several years in becoming really good at that, it wouldn't have helped me get to where I wanted to go. And so there isn't an easy answer here, but just recognize, if you're only bringing one thing to the table, eventually the technology is going to move past that one thing. And so how are you going to future proof yourself?

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:31.000
Awesome. And I wish that I had a better answer, too, because I've really struggled with this for a really, really long time. People are telling me I should do this, or I'm being really encouraged to do this, and it doesn't come easy to me. And I'm thinking, oh, I just must have a willpower problem where I should be able to power through and do this thing.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:17:00.000
And it turns out, no, what benefited me most was doing the thing that came more fluidly to me and more easy to me, and really prioritizing it. So thank you, anonymous question asker, that was great. And there's a sort of follow-up question that flows really nicely to this from Arsenis in Slido, and so I would love it if Arsenis could unmute and ask that for us, and I will highlight it in Slido so everybody can see it, pop it in the chat.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:03.000
Cool. Thank you, Libby.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:04.000
Hey.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:30.000
Yeah, thanks for joining us. Is it Paula's side? Thank you for joining us today and sharing your experience with us. So my question is, given all the ambiguity around data-related titles and role definitions, what are some of the ways that you think a data professional can best communicate their skills to the market so that they can actually land in a role

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:33.000
that makes sense for them? So yeah.

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:36.000
Yeah.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:48.000
So one thing you can do is, if you just spend a lot of time on LinkedIn and if you can find people who are already in the roles that you want to have, how are they talking about themselves?

00:17:48.000 --> 00:18:03.000
If you can reach out, even if companies aren't hiring, if you can network with people who run teams who have the type of role you want to have, reach out to that person, especially if they're not hiring, because that means they aren't getting a lot of outreaches, and just see if they'll have a casual coffee chat with you.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:24.000
You can make a guess and blindly have hypotheses about how you should market yourself, but the best way to test your hypothesis is talk to the people that you would sell your experience to and find out what lands the most with them. Let them tell you what they're looking for and what the market wants.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:28.000
Yeah.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:39.000
That's where I always get the advice to talk about your impact. We'll talk about the business impact you had. And I'm like, on all these data projects that like went nowhere or failed or like an app that nobody used.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:42.000
It's always so tough. Okay.

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:46.000
Arsenis, thank you so much for your question.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:49.000
I have the same question over and over again.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:52.000
