I have a question from Rachel that I wanted to let her talk about. Rachel, do you want to ask that one?

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:14.000
Yeah, Pell is when you were talking about helping people translate their ideas into a language that resonates with stakeholders. I was wondering if you could give us a specific example or one that like comes to mind for you right away.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:16.000
Yes, just give me a moment to think of one.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.000
Okay.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:32.000
I think a common theme is stakeholder asks for dashboards. I want to be able to slice this dashboard by date, country, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, like 10 to 15 micromanaging slices the data.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:49.000
And whenever I get those sort of requests, my initial thinking is, yeah, you don't know what you're actually looking for. You just want to ask for everything just assuming if I if I work for a week or two, putting together every different slice of this dashboard, you'll finally have that magic aha moment.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:20:03.000
And so you don't actually know what you want. And so whenever I get a very detailed ask that has like 10 to 15 different sub segments in it, that tells me let me go have a conversation with that person.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:15.000
What are you trying to accomplish with this? What are you going to do with this data? What are you going to do if the data is informative and it validates your hypothesis? What are you going to do if the data negates your hypothesis?

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:30.000
What are you going to do if the data is muddy? And then I check to see, do I get different answers? Because if the stakeholder tells me, well, if the data is positive, I'm going to do X. And if the data is negative, I'm going to do X. And if the data is blurry, I'm going to do X.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:33.000
Well, now we no longer have a data driven decision.

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:42.000
This stakeholder already knows what they want to do. And so understand why they want to do it that way. And then think about what are the pitfalls?

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:52.000
Well, the problem is they're not thinking about this long term holdout. And this idea they have, they're not taking into account all of the users that aren't going to have access to that feature.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:21:06.000
So instead of just providing them a dashboard of all the 10 to 15 different cuts, I'm going to also provide them information on how things are performing over and above the holdout so they can actually see what level of incremental value they're driving.

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:21.000
They didn't ask for the incremental value functionality. They didn't ask for the holdout visibility. But that's going to actually tell them if they're on track to accomplish their goals. And so you have to understand what they want to accomplish.

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:31.000
And then you have to use your own statistical knowledge to figure out, based on what's in my toolkit, what can I easily provide them that will actually answer their questions?

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:49.000
Thank you. Do you ever see it going the other way as well, where a data scientist has a really great idea for something, but they have to convince stakeholders that this is something they should pursue and then putting it in their stakeholder language?

00:21:50.000 --> 00:22:02.000
That happens all the time, because sometimes the things we want to pursue, in order to explain them, we have to go into a level of mathiness that no one actually wants to listen to. And that's hard.

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:17.000
You know, it's pretty common for the first time I pitch ideas for them to be rejected. And I often think of in a business context, when someone tells me no, that means that this idea is not yet a fit for where the business is.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:31.000
And so once I think about, okay, this idea is not yet ripe, what are the things that are holding the idea back? What do they care about right now? How can I turn a not yet into a yes?

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:39.000
And that, again, you have to empathize with your audience and understand what they care about to get that no to a yes.

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:55.000
I like that. I also like thinking about listening to stakeholders and the way that they are saying things and the words that they are using to describe them in all of your conversations, and then ask yourself if you are using the same language back to them or not.

00:22:56.000 --> 00:23:09.000
One thing that's always been challenging to me here is that the advice always seems to go towards the data scientist or the analyst or the data people to talk more like stakeholders, but the advice doesn't ever seem to go the other direction.

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:16.000
Like, hey, business people, learn more data stuff, be more data literate, talk more like a data scientist.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:26.000
I would love to emphasize that it can go both ways. Both sides can be more aware of how the other is talking.

