00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:02.000
All right. Quick minute for Marlene.

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:08.000
So I'll speak from personal experience. I was unemployed for almost a full year.

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:17.000
Imagine trying to live on your savings and almost being ready to empty your retirement account after a year because, frankly, it's just hard to pay for things on unemployment.

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:30.000
So I very quickly, I have, like, a lot of coding background, but I've also just been like a figure it out as I go person and I will handle the task at hand and whatever's on fire, I put it out and that kind of deal.

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:38.000
In the job market, I got several applications that asked specifically, how much experience do you have in health care?

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:42.000
How much experience do you have in HR? How much experience do you have in this?

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:49.000
Right. And depending on what I was applying for, if I put less than one year, my resume went into the dumpster.

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:52.000
Like, I could just tell I wasn't even getting responses back.

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:56.000
If you are experiencing this, I feel for you. My heart goes out to you.

00:24:56.000 --> 00:25:01.000
It is not easy. Cry yourself to sleep, rock yourself, whatever you need to to get through it.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:05.000
Call mental health lines if you need phone a friend. But it is really rough.

00:25:05.000 --> 00:25:15.000
I highly suggest I'm not saying lie, but I think it's worth going into an interview and saying, I know your company does this.

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:20.000
I haven't done a lot in that. But here's what I've studied in just prepping for this interview.

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:25.000
And I want you to know that I can learn the domain knowledge very quickly.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:30.000
But these are the tools that I have ready to go. That's going to take your company to the next level.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:35.000
All that being said, I got to second round interviews doing that, and it was great.

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:39.000
But what got me the job was knowing somebody. So build your network.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:42.000
I love this hangout for so many reasons. Thank you so much.

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:49.000
You have Ted and Marcos and all the folks that I've made friends with here, Rachel and Libby, too.

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:54.000
These are the folks that help you realize, like, there's a world outside of unemployment.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:26:01.000
So other than mental health, right, it's good to just know who's hiring and what.

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:06.000
You know, I think I peened one other person on this call and said, hey, I'm interested in a job that's kind of in your field.

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:09.000
Like, can you give me like the ups and downs of your field?

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:13.000
And even that was valuable because I realized very quickly I didn't want to go into that work.

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:16.000
So build your network. That's what we're all here for. It takes a village.

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:20.000
And there's my quick diatribe. Does that help, Libby? Yes. Awesome.

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:25.000
And that is really valuable, like finding out what you don't want. It can be super, super valuable.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:29.000
Because what you do want, you're looking at a really broad target.

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:32.000
Like of all of these things, what do I want?

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:39.000
But when you figure out what you don't want, it tends to be pretty specific and easy to avoid or steer clear of.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:41.000
Awesome. Thank you so much.

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:45.000
And you can say you want the code, but the truth is a player is going to hear,

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:49.000
I have to hire somebody to do something manually that ChatGPT can do, unfortunately.

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:54.000
So instead you have to do the data science speak where I translate things more.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:27:02.000
And like Pals, like I can think about your greater needs and put it in data speak to feed to a ChatGPT model and or confer with other scientists.

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:08.000
So I'll also tell you that you have to learn how to kind of speak that language a bit now or else employers aren't going to hear it.

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:12.000
They're just going to think you're going to be overpaid for a lot of extra work.

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:21.000
Well, speaking of like ways that our our industry is sort of evolving, Rohan had a question about this very, very thing.

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:24.000
So I would love it if Rohan could unmute and ask his.

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:31.000
Hello. Can you guys hear me? Yes. Great.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:37.000
Hi, Pals. So my question is, given how quickly the data science field is evolving,

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:45.000
do you have any best practices or tips on basically keeping up or staying ahead with the data science field?

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:59.000
I'll be very honest. One of the reasons I went into management and leadership was because staying on top of the latest coding trends,

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:04.000
it was something I should be doing, but it was not a natural strength of mine.

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:10.000
Whereas understanding the needs of technical stakeholders and business stakeholders and connecting those dots,

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:17.000
that was something that I knew I was particularly good at and the people around me weren't.

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:25.000
And so if you think about the things that you do better naturally than everyone around you,

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:32.000
and then you think about, well, how is AI going to magnify that?

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:38.000
How can I leverage AI and what's coming next to enhance my strengths?

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:43.000
That's not a very specific answer, but that's like a lot of what I do in my coaching practices,

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:49.000
helping people understand their strengths and then figure out how do you now future-proof yourself

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:56.000
and make sure that when that next generation, because I'm a millennial, and so Gen Z came up and they were hungry,

00:28:56.000 --> 00:29:00.000
and next Gen Alpha is going to come up and they're going to be really hungry too.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:07.000
And so what are you going to do that's unique to you that no one else can be as you as well as you can?

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:12.000
Like you're the best at being you.

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:17.000
It's a lesson that we've been trying to teach ourselves since childhood, right?

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:21.000
Like be yourself, just be you, you're great.

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:29.000
And yet some of us, I mean, I'm almost 40 and I'm like, wow, it's taken me a really long time to embrace that lesson

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:33.000
and realize that me as myself, I do have value.

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:35.000
The things that I like to do do have value.

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:38.000
Yours, everybody, you do too.

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:41.000
All right, Rohan, thank you so much for the question.

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:48.000
Let's move to Cecilia and Cecilia cannot unmute, but she would like to know what drew you to coaching

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:52.000
after such a strong technical and leadership career?

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:56.000
I bet it just came along with the territory of leadership, huh?

00:29:56.000 --> 00:30:02.000
I mean, the favorite part of my job was having one-on-ones with my team.

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:05.000
And I was laid off two months ago on April 1st.

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:10.000
And I had to think about, all right, well, the market's in a weird spot.

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:13.000
What do I want to be, how do I want to be spending my time?

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:17.000
Well, in my job, my favorite way to spend my time was having one-on-ones with my team.

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:22.000
Wait a second, coaching is just all one-on-ones.

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:25.000
I'd have to figure out how to meet people and how to connect with people.

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:32.000
But there are ways that I don't need to find a company to pay me to have one-on-ones with people.

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:35.000
I can just talk to the people directly.

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:40.000
And if I'm providing value and they want to meet with me and I want to meet with them, we'll figure out how to make it work.

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:46.000
And so, you know, I'm only two months into my coaching career, but I'm really enjoying it so far.

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:48.000
And I've had a lot of fascinating conversations.

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:51.000
And, you know, I am seeking my next role.

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:56.000
Coaching was just something that was going to help keep me busy while I was unemployed.

00:30:56.000 --> 00:31:01.000
And it's possible my coaching takes off and then full-time employment doesn't make sense.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:05.000
We're having a bit of a race condition here to see which happens first.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:11.000
Yeah, I feel like the question of how long you've been coaching, though, is not like two months.

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:16.000
If you're a leader, you've been coaching people for years and years and years.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:22.000
The pay structure is just different because freelancing is difficult, as I will attest.

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:25.000
Cecilia, thank you for your amazing question.

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:28.000
I have another question here from Lolo.

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:32.000
If you are able to unmute and ask, that would be great.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:38.000
If not, let me know in the chat and I can ask for you as well.

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:42.000
And I will put your question here in the chat.

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:44.000
Sure, that's fine.

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:45.000
Hey.

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:47.000
Hey, hello.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:54.000
Yeah, so I was just trying to pick your brain, trying to refine my approach when it comes to stakeholder management.

00:31:54.000 --> 00:32:03.000
When you're interacting with business stakeholders, is there any particular fundamental structure you use that you recommend during meetings?

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:10.000
And what's usually the most crucial agreement or insights that you hope to take out of those meetings?

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:19.000
So the first thing I do, if I have a particularly difficult stakeholder that I'm not winning over, I'm going to ask them for a casual coffee chat.

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:21.000
I want to get to know them interpersonally.

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:22.000
I want to know what they do on the weekend.

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:24.000
I want to hear about their pets.

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:27.000
I want to see photos of their pets or their kids or whatever.

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:32.000
I want to build a connection where they're going to give me the benefit of the doubt.

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:43.000
Because once they see me as a human, they're going to be more inclined to be patient with me, to listen to what I have to say, to not jump to conclusions.

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:47.000
And I'm going to be doing the same for them because now I care about them as a human as well.

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:53.000
And so I think the trap is to think of your...

00:32:54.140 --> 00:32:59.020
The trap is to think of your stakeholders

00:32:59.020 --> 00:33:03.260
is just like barriers or obstacles or another subsystem

00:33:03.260 --> 00:33:06.260
or just like a technical component and their people.

00:33:06.260 --> 00:33:09.140
And it's rare for, especially for technical people,

00:33:09.140 --> 00:33:10.900
it's rare for a technical person

00:33:10.900 --> 00:33:12.540
to reach out to a business stakeholder and say,

00:33:12.540 --> 00:33:14.740
hey, I just like to get to know you better

00:33:14.740 --> 00:33:17.740
and about your career and how you got to your position.

00:33:17.740 --> 00:33:20.520
And when you actually show interest in people,

00:33:20.520 --> 00:33:23.059
the dynamics of the conversation changes

00:33:23.080 --> 00:33:24.760
and then you're having a dialogue

00:33:24.760 --> 00:33:26.959
as opposed to people just shutting you down.

00:33:29.599 --> 00:33:31.119
Awesome.

00:33:31.119 --> 00:33:33.680
Thank you so much, Lulu.

00:33:33.680 --> 00:33:35.599
I hope that that helped answer your question.

00:33:35.599 --> 00:33:37.919
I heartily agree.

00:33:37.919 --> 00:33:39.560
And I don't think I need to tell anybody

00:33:39.560 --> 00:33:41.919
that I'm a fan of making friends

00:33:41.919 --> 00:33:43.439
with everybody that you talk to

00:33:43.439 --> 00:33:47.720
and instead of networking, just make friends.

00:33:47.720 --> 00:33:51.360
I also will say one thing that I find really helpful

00:33:51.380 --> 00:33:55.020
is just avoiding corpo-speak.

00:33:55.020 --> 00:33:57.699
It helps people see you as an actual human being

00:33:57.699 --> 00:34:00.500
and not a corporate avatar of yourself.

00:34:00.500 --> 00:34:02.779
And so when you want people to,

00:34:04.059 --> 00:34:05.959
like Paola said, give you the benefit of the doubt,

00:34:05.959 --> 00:34:08.599
trust you, have real conversations with you,

00:34:08.599 --> 00:34:12.260
be patient with you, talking like a regular human being,

00:34:12.260 --> 00:34:15.459
like you're their neighbor can be so helpful.

00:34:15.459 --> 00:34:16.760
Alrighty.

00:34:16.760 --> 00:34:20.379
I have a question from Zach and it has an asterisk.

00:34:20.379 --> 00:34:22.800
So I will ask it for him.

00:34:22.800 --> 00:34:25.720
And that is, how do you expect the career landscape

00:34:25.720 --> 00:34:27.400
to change in the next few years?

00:34:27.400 --> 00:34:29.800
But Zach, I wanna pin onto the end of this

00:34:29.800 --> 00:34:31.519
and say also like, how have you seen

00:34:31.519 --> 00:34:33.720
the career landscape change

00:34:33.720 --> 00:34:36.959
because you've been in data for a really long time?

00:34:36.959 --> 00:34:38.360
Yeah.

00:34:38.360 --> 00:34:39.879
I mean, when I started my career

00:34:39.879 --> 00:34:41.760
and I know that this is gonna make everyone

00:34:41.760 --> 00:34:43.320
on this call cringe a little bit,

00:34:43.320 --> 00:34:45.080
but I'm gonna say it anyway.

00:34:45.080 --> 00:34:48.559
I did most of my work in Excel when I started my career.

00:34:49.059 --> 00:34:53.300
And then we moved to automation and I learned SQL

00:34:53.300 --> 00:34:56.820
and I learned Python and I'd used R a bit in college.

00:34:56.820 --> 00:34:58.980
And then I learned some machine learning techniques

00:34:58.980 --> 00:35:00.699
and then it became Bayesian.

00:35:00.699 --> 00:35:02.539
And then it turned in more into deep learning.

00:35:02.539 --> 00:35:03.580
I was like, oh, that's wizardry.

00:35:03.580 --> 00:35:05.059
I'm not ready to learn.

00:35:05.059 --> 00:35:08.399
I'm gonna hire someone else to think about that stuff.

00:35:08.399 --> 00:35:11.979
But I've seen the sophistication grow and grow and grow.

00:35:11.979 --> 00:35:13.740
And now with AI coming,

00:35:13.740 --> 00:35:15.740
there's almost like this critical point

00:35:15.740 --> 00:35:17.460
where just being a tech,

00:35:17.460 --> 00:35:20.919
it used to be the more technical

00:35:20.919 --> 00:35:23.639
and the more statistical wizardry you knew,

00:35:23.639 --> 00:35:25.479
the easier it was to get a job.

00:35:25.479 --> 00:35:27.199
And now I think there's this pendulum

00:35:27.199 --> 00:35:28.520
swinging the other way,

00:35:28.520 --> 00:35:30.720
which is if you're just a technician,

00:35:30.720 --> 00:35:33.479
it gets harder unless you're one of those few

00:35:33.479 --> 00:35:36.679
that have the PhD that are working on the LLMs,

00:35:36.679 --> 00:35:41.679
helping open AI and Claude and chat GPT

00:35:41.679 --> 00:35:42.520
and all of that stuff.

00:35:42.520 --> 00:35:45.300
If you're not in that niche domain,

00:35:45.300 --> 00:35:48.759
just being a technician probably isn't enough.

00:35:48.759 --> 00:35:51.160
And so how are you expanding your impact

00:35:51.160 --> 00:35:54.860
in terms of maybe as a data scientist,

00:35:54.860 --> 00:35:56.279
you wanna expand your impact,

00:35:56.279 --> 00:35:58.360
but you want it to be technical still.

00:35:58.360 --> 00:35:59.600
And so you wanna demonstrate,

00:35:59.600 --> 00:36:01.160
well, I can do all of my data engineering

00:36:01.160 --> 00:36:03.559
as well as all of my data science,

00:36:03.559 --> 00:36:05.320
as well as all my analytics engineering

00:36:05.320 --> 00:36:06.520
and dashboarding, et cetera.

00:36:06.520 --> 00:36:08.919
And so you wanna demonstrate that you have extra value

00:36:08.919 --> 00:36:09.759
because you don't have

00:36:09.759 --> 00:36:12.539
just the typical data science skillset.

00:36:12.539 --> 00:36:14.139
Maybe you're a technician,

00:36:14.160 --> 00:36:15.440
but you also wanna learn how to do

00:36:15.440 --> 00:36:16.960
some software development as well,

00:36:16.960 --> 00:36:20.039
or you wanna show that you can build apps with AI.

00:36:20.039 --> 00:36:23.279
How can you be more than just the person

00:36:23.279 --> 00:36:25.800
who writes models in R and Python?

00:36:25.800 --> 00:36:28.699
How can you be something plus that?

00:36:30.559 --> 00:36:32.119
Yes, I like that.

00:36:32.119 --> 00:36:35.720
And I've gotta say, no shame, no hate to Excel.

00:36:35.720 --> 00:36:37.160
We all still use it.

00:36:37.160 --> 00:36:40.160
And there's so much Excel love and support

00:36:40.160 --> 00:36:41.000
in the chat right now.

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:43.539
If you are listening or watching this later

00:36:43.600 --> 00:36:45.160
and you're like, oh, I use Excel.

00:36:45.160 --> 00:36:46.199
I also love Excel.

00:36:46.199 --> 00:36:48.440
So do we all, yes.

00:36:48.440 --> 00:36:51.720
And Excel is, as several people have said in the chat,

00:36:51.720 --> 00:36:54.460
I think Excel is a gateway drug where you're like,

00:36:54.460 --> 00:36:56.199
Excel is fantastic until it's not,

00:36:56.199 --> 00:36:57.600
and then you need something more.

00:36:57.600 --> 00:37:01.240
And that's often how many of us end up coding

00:37:01.240 --> 00:37:04.759
or doing code-first analytics is because we needed that.

00:37:04.759 --> 00:37:08.000
So Zach, thank you so much for the question.

00:37:09.119 --> 00:37:12.519
I have a question from Kyle as well.

00:37:12.519 --> 00:37:15.299
Kyle, I don't know if you are available to ask this.

00:37:15.299 --> 00:37:17.220
I want to say, I don't think that you are,

00:37:17.220 --> 00:37:19.859
but maybe, let me see.

00:37:22.940 --> 00:37:24.700
Yeah, I can ask.

00:37:24.700 --> 00:37:26.019
There he is, yay, thanks.

00:37:26.019 --> 00:37:27.459
Yeah, thank you.

00:37:27.459 --> 00:37:29.459
So I have a friend that works in the industry

00:37:29.459 --> 00:37:31.660
and I know it's a sample of one,

00:37:31.660 --> 00:37:35.140
but when he's evaluating candidates,

00:37:35.140 --> 00:37:36.820
he looks at their GitHub profile.

00:37:36.820 --> 00:37:39.260
So how much does your GitHub profile weigh

00:37:39.260 --> 00:37:40.880
into job candidacy?

00:37:40.880 --> 00:37:43.200
And do you find it to be more important

00:37:43.200 --> 00:37:44.399
than other tangibles?

00:37:48.140 --> 00:37:50.260
Not how you have profile.

00:37:50.260 --> 00:37:51.959
I'm just gonna put that out there.

00:37:53.160 --> 00:37:55.480
I think it really depends on the role

00:37:55.480 --> 00:37:58.519
and the type of company you're interviewing with.

00:37:58.519 --> 00:38:00.040
There are companies where absolutely

00:38:00.040 --> 00:38:01.600
that's a non-negotiable.

00:38:01.600 --> 00:38:03.239
And you need to have that,

00:38:03.239 --> 00:38:04.799
and you need to have recent,

00:38:04.799 --> 00:38:06.320
it's not just you need a profile,

00:38:06.320 --> 00:38:08.640
you need recent commits in a language

00:38:08.679 --> 00:38:11.200
that they care about working on a problem

00:38:11.200 --> 00:38:12.760
that's similar to the problems they work on.

00:38:12.760 --> 00:38:15.799
And so this goes back to a question from earlier,

00:38:15.799 --> 00:38:18.519
which is, talk to the people

00:38:18.519 --> 00:38:20.320
that are in the roles you want to have,

00:38:20.320 --> 00:38:22.339
talk to the hiring managers,

00:38:22.339 --> 00:38:23.880
especially the ones that aren't currently hiring

00:38:23.880 --> 00:38:26.239
because they're not swamped with LinkedIn requests,

00:38:26.239 --> 00:38:29.200
but talk to the people who are managers

00:38:29.200 --> 00:38:30.760
at companies you want to work at,

00:38:30.760 --> 00:38:33.160
and they can tell you how important that is.

00:38:34.440 --> 00:38:37.519
Over my career, I've only had two roles

00:38:37.519 --> 00:38:39.839
where I actively checked the GitHub commits,

00:38:39.839 --> 00:38:42.000
and it was because it was a really niche problem

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:43.399
I needed them to solve.

00:38:43.399 --> 00:38:45.000
And I needed to know that they had

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:47.839
very, very relevant domain experience,

00:38:47.839 --> 00:38:50.579
but I haven't checked GitHub profiles

00:38:50.579 --> 00:38:54.079
for most of the roles I hire for,

00:38:54.079 --> 00:38:55.920
but that's not true everywhere.

00:38:55.920 --> 00:38:59.200
It really just depends on the actual industry itself

00:38:59.200 --> 00:39:01.399
and the type of company you want to work at.

00:39:02.839 --> 00:39:04.399
Awesome, thank you.

00:39:04.399 --> 00:39:07.519
And pulling in some stuff from the chat verbally,

00:39:07.519 --> 00:39:10.760
Marco says, we never decide to interview

