00:47:29.840 --> 00:47:34.119
With the increase in vibe coding and LLMs writing code,

00:47:34.119 --> 00:47:36.039
do you think that explainability

00:47:36.039 --> 00:47:38.640
and interpretability in data science

00:47:38.640 --> 00:47:40.200
have risen in importance?

00:47:40.200 --> 00:47:43.799
So as data scientists, like should data scientists

00:47:43.799 --> 00:47:48.080
be better decision makers than they are coders?

00:47:48.080 --> 00:47:49.520
Really interesting question.

00:47:52.599 --> 00:47:55.119
I'd like to say the answer is an easy yes,

00:47:55.119 --> 00:47:57.359
but I'm hesitating and I'll explain why.

00:47:59.440 --> 00:48:04.440
I have been in situations where it's really hard

00:48:06.039 --> 00:48:08.200
to make the business decision

00:48:08.200 --> 00:48:10.520
and no one knows the right answer.

00:48:10.520 --> 00:48:12.239
And so they turn to the person

00:48:12.239 --> 00:48:15.000
who can produce the most sophisticated math.

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:18.479
And so while I do think interpretability,

00:48:18.479 --> 00:48:20.880
explainability is really important,

00:48:20.880 --> 00:48:25.719
there is always going to be that one category of problems

00:48:25.719 --> 00:48:30.719
and let's call it 20% where no one knows the right answer.

00:48:31.479 --> 00:48:32.919
So they're gonna defer to the person

00:48:32.919 --> 00:48:35.359
who can make the most complicated math

00:48:35.400 --> 00:48:39.760
and be a little intellectually intimidating.

00:48:39.760 --> 00:48:41.280
I don't think that's the way

00:48:41.280 --> 00:48:43.440
you can actually build your career,

00:48:43.440 --> 00:48:45.559
but I don't think that category of problem

00:48:45.559 --> 00:48:47.400
is going to go away.

00:48:47.400 --> 00:48:50.719
So I do think in general, explainability,

00:48:50.719 --> 00:48:52.760
interpretability is very important,

00:48:52.760 --> 00:48:55.640
but that one category I think is always going to exist

00:48:55.640 --> 00:48:59.039
because when humans don't know, we don't like the unknown.

00:48:59.039 --> 00:49:01.440
And so that thing we understand the least

00:49:01.440 --> 00:49:04.080
that seems really confident, let's just go with that.

00:49:05.520 --> 00:49:06.559
Yeah.

00:49:06.559 --> 00:49:10.640
My two cents on this one is that trust in AI

00:49:10.640 --> 00:49:12.239
is a very interesting topic

00:49:12.239 --> 00:49:15.719
and it's something that's evolving and being studied a lot,

00:49:15.719 --> 00:49:19.159
but it's been studied also just as like trust

00:49:19.159 --> 00:49:20.559
in predictive models in general,

00:49:20.559 --> 00:49:23.119
outside of LLMs or before LLMs.

00:49:24.440 --> 00:49:26.880
And a lot of times when you look at the results

00:49:26.880 --> 00:49:31.640
of those studies, humans were trusting their own judgment

00:49:31.640 --> 00:49:34.280
more than a computer output of a prediction.

00:49:34.280 --> 00:49:37.679
And so having that human being in the loop is definitely,

00:49:38.559 --> 00:49:40.000
I think, still really valuable

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:42.200
to a lot of people individually

00:49:42.200 --> 00:49:45.239
when it comes down to them making a decision.

00:49:45.239 --> 00:49:47.760
So keep that in mind and use that as ammo

00:49:47.760 --> 00:49:49.520
when you're talking to other people.

